body:
> You could make a generic method on Sprite that takes an T: FnOnce, does the setup, calls the function, then cleans up.

This eases creation of text sprites, as mentioned in #35 - maybe enough to close that issue?  I wish they were as easy to manage as in Lua, but separate improvement ideas should probably be new issues.

---

An example usage: if you're using sprites and text, Panic recommends writing your text into bitmaps held by sprites.  This helps avoid timing issues, since updating and drawing sprites clears previously drawn text. Inside with_context, any drawing calls are relative to your bitmap.`

```rust
let graphics = Graphics::get();
let sprite_manager = SpriteManager::get_mut();
let background = LCDColor::Solid(LCDSolidColor::kColorWhite);
let mut text_bitmap = graphics.new_bitmap(size2(40, 20), background)?;
graphics.with_context(&mut text_bitmap, || {
    graphics.draw_text("test", point2(0, 0))?;
    Ok(())
})?;
let mut text_sprite = sprite_manager.new_sprite()?;
text_sprite.set_image(text_bitmap, LCDBitmapFlip::kBitmapUnflipped)?;
text_sprite.move_to(200.0, 120.0)?;
sprite_manager.add_sprite(&text_sprite)?;
```
